NAME:
  strmod

DESCRIPTION:
  strmod tests or performs an operation on a string using pipe syntax

AVAILABLE PARAMETERS:
  $1 - operation      [the type of operation or test to run against the string]

SUBCOMMANDS:
  trim            Trim the extra whitespace of the string
  collapse        Joins new lines of the string
  to_upper        Transform the case of the string to uppercase
  to_lower        Transform the case of the string to lowercase
  to_title        Transform the case of the string to title case
  to_camel        Transform the case of the string to camel case
  slugify         Replace spaces with provided character (default is '_')
  trim_suffix     Trim string suffix of provided string (default is whitespace)
  trim_prefix     Trim string prefix of provided string (default is whitespace)
  strip           Trim string prefix (1st arg) and suffix (2nd arg -- or 1st arg when no 2nd arg provided)
  replace         Find & replace the provided string (1st arg) with other provided string (2nd arg)
  regex_replace   RegEx find & replace using provided 1st arg as find string pattern & 2nd arg as replace string
  length          Returns length of the string
  count           Returns the number of times a sub-string occurs in the string
  chars           Count total number of characters in the string
  words           Count total number of words in the string
  lines           Returns number of lines of the string, or number of lines containing provided sub-string
  endswith        Test whether the string ends with the provided sub-string (returns true/false)
  startswith      Test whether the string starts with the provided sub-string (returns true/false)
  empty           Test whether the string is empty (returns true/false)
  contains        Test whether the string contains the provided sub-string (returns true/false)
  append          Appends the provided sub-string
  prepend         Prepends the provided sub-string
  wrap            Wraps the string with the provided prefix (1st arg) and suffix (2nd arg)


OPTIONS:
  -h, --help          [show this help documentation]

SYNOPSIS:
  strmod operation [$1] [$2]

EXAMPLES:
  echo "a string" | strmod to_upper                             # A STRING
  echo "another string" | strmod contains "string"              # true
  echo "yet another string" | strmod length                     # 18
  echo "yet another string" | strmod startswith "another"       # false
  echo "yet another string" | strmod count " "                  # 2
  echo "yet\n another \nstring" | strmod lines                  # 3
  echo "small string" | strmod replace 'small' 'tiny'           # tiny string
  echo "string 1" | strmod regex_replace '(.*?)[ ].*' '\1_2'    # string_2
  echo "::string::" | strmod strip ':' '::'                     # :string
  echo "::string::" | strmod strip '::' | strmod count ':'                   # :string
